<tr><td class="printline">
<span class="name"><a name="97610"></a></span><span class="postdetails">#1:&nbsp;<font color=black><b>After Beta in EQ2 and playing WoW, my opinion on MMROPG's</b> Author:&nbsp;<b>Gnarl</b>,&nbsp;</font></span><span class="postdetails"><font color=black></font></span>
<a href="viewtopic.php?p=97610#97610"><img src="templates/subSilver/images/icon_minipost.gif" width="12" height="9" alt="Post" title="Post" border="0" /></a><span class="postdetails"><font color=black>Posted: Thu Feb 24, 2005 1:36 pm</font><span class="gen"><br>
</td></tr>
<tr><td class="printline">
<span class="postbody">Yes, I know, this is a topic liable to cause problems.  I'm not here to do that.  I just feel the need to make some observations that I've noted while in EQ, in Beta of EQ2 and playing WoW (as well as CoH).  Folks, though I will speak to direct experience, please understand that this should be taken first as opinion.  I'll try to remain as objective as I can, and am not out to insult anyone, but, in some cases my thoughts will not be very flattering about the course the industry seems to be taking (as evidenced by the new games).
<br />

<br />
I'll zero in on three aspects of these games that I consider to be very basic and key concepts: pulling, solo/grouping, and Critter (mb) difficulty.  I'll use all three of these as a way of intrudicing the problems I see with strategy and tactics.  I'll start with familiar ground to lay the framework that I want to compare and contrast, so, we'll start with observations about EQ:
<br />

<br />
Generally speaking, EQ is a very social game, we all know this.  However, it's also a game that requires a lot of strategy and tactics to do well.  An example of this is single pulling and figuring out how to manage this.  Monks were the first to really shine in this arena, Bards and finally Enchanters do this job very well.  Most classes have some tools for doing this but by no means all.  Save, of course, that if working with a team, you can always 'train' a group of mobs and have a buddy pick one or two off with a bow from the clot that is chasing you, all classes can manage this in one form or another.  The key, though, is that we have to consider how we are going to pull mobs from a given camp.  We can't afford to just wade in swinging as that is certain death, assuming, of course, that the mobs are blue or better cons.
<br />

<br />
Oddly, the Devs seemed to think that this was a problem and have taken steps to either elliminate the need (in recent expansions) for quality pulling, or elliminate the ability to single pull (by stacking mobs to thickly, or making targetting impossible: SRo LDoN anyone).  I find this odd since having to think about what I'm doing is part of what makes a game enjoyable.  Worse yet, is the reaction to orphaning classes or relegating them to one primary role, as Enchanters and Monks in recent changes of EQ.  No, I agree, we still have a role in certain places, but, even as far back as the Revamp of CT, we should've seen this coming.  Sony took what was THE proving ground for CC and made it a zone where you'd better know CC very well before you get into the zone.  Oddly, that zone is now severely underpopulated where I rarely saw a camp open with the old CT.
<br />

<br />
Suffice it to say, that EQ, up through PoP, was a game not only of hack and slash, and of socialization but one of intellect.  A player had to think through his classes mechanics and how that class interacted, or meshed, with other classes to excel.  You could PL your way up, but, if you did, in my experience, you were always missing some aspect of the class and thus not playing it up to full speed.  Same goes with Soloing, I have the utmost respect for soloists, but, you could not work out your group mechanics through this methocology.  In all cases, to do well, the game required knowledge and skill.
<br />

<br />
In EQ, all mobs are of the same difficulty level.  Ie: if a mob is level 50, it's level 50.  Ther eis no concept of a level 50 group mob, or a level 50 solo mob, or a level 50 raid mob.  yes, there are mobs that are underconned and overconned, but, fact is there is no reliable method of referring to a mob and knowing that it was designed for a group, or a raid, just by conning it.  If it's blue, you know it's a bit below your level (or more at higher levels) and thus something that you might be able to take out.  Depending on the mobs abilities, your class will have an easier, o rharder, time of taking down said Critter alone.  Typically, at least in the early days, if you saw a red con surrounded by blue cons, you knew that the red was designed for at least a group to tackle.  Typically, you would not engage a red con critter without a group anyway, and  in my experience, it's always been better to kill a thousand blues quickly, than a hundred reds slowly, so, we would avoid the reds, when hunting exp, and zero in on the blues.  I'll reiterate: there is no obvious mechanic for determining the power of one critter related to another, given that the two critters had the came con.  You were forced to experiment to find out that this critter was 'underconned' or that crittter was 'overconned.'
<br />

<br />
I'll add one more note: I originally came to EQ from UO.  In UO I found the society to be very backstabbing and 'me' oriented.  Ie: each character was out for themselves and was not only not going to help you, but, if they found you in need of help, they'd found an easy target.  I found that I was alwys very 'nervous' in UO and I very much appreciated the change when coming to EQ.  I like the challenge of PvP, but, I also like the relaxation of not having to worry about someone just off screen waiting for me to finish the critter so that they can stab me in the back while I'm low on HPs and they are fresh.  Better, in EQ I found a community that was automatically helping of everyone around them, new to the game or old jockie.  I'll skip this section in EQ2 because I found the crowd in EQ2 to be largely as helpful as hte one in EQ.  I should also ad that the tenor an dnature of the community in EQ has had it's ups and downs.  It seems that on occasion we get an influx of jerks and the rudeness follows, but, that doesn't seem to last very long.  I've always felt there was something in the very nature of EQ that fostered a helping hand attitude, but, I'll be darned if I've ever been able to put my finger on what it is that causes this.
<br />

<br />
EQ2:
<br />

<br />
Now we have a game where each class stands out on it's own.  Admittedly, I did not play through to high levels, but, the levels I did play through, I was perfectly capable of soloing anywhere I went.  Pulling was trivial.  Target a mob, and you know, straight off, if you were going to get a single or multiples.  Gone were the days of trying to figure out mob interaction, pacifying, mez puling or charm pulling.  I found no use for mez save in group situations.  Even then, since all classes can, virtually, stand alone, I found group discipline to be lacking and the argument for discipline to be lacking.  Simply stated: I found no use for mez, it was too easy just to let the group split tank and kill them all, while I nuked.  Yes, I had mez, yes it worked, but, when facing a pull of 4 or 5 mobs, mezzing one... or 2, was not going to make a differeence.  Better to move off and find a single pull mob: one that was not chained to other mobs.  Note that there is also no mechanic for peeling off one mob from a train, as if you aggro one of a group, you WILL aggro all of them.  The closest I was able to get was that if you pulled a group, killed one, and were able to run away far enough to lose them, when I returned, I'd see one fewer in the group I'd pulled (but, that one would usually respawn fairly quickly).
<br />

<br />
Group mechanics are more important here, though.  This is due to the fact hat Group heroic opportunities can have a great impact on battle.  Thus, you do need to know which HOs to hit when to coordinate with your fellow group mates.  However, this equates to knowing which actions correcpond to which icon and hitting the appropriate hitkey to fire that action at the right time.  It would take little or no time to figure out which HOs worked best together (there ARE cases where you can have more than one action fit the same icon).  Thus, you really only have to know your own class, and which icons fit with which of your classes actions.  Once that is known, it's a matter of wachint the HO Wheel for an opportunity to strike.  To me, this makes the group tactics and interaction a bit too easy.  That said, it is, in my opinion, a good mechanic.  The least I can say is that it does promote, and provide an advantage, to grouping, where it does not provide any great disadvantage to soloing.
<br />

<br />
In EQ2, you have an indicator of how tough a mob is above and beyond hte con colors.  A small icon in the name would show that a critter was designed to be a group critter, or a single critter or a raid critter.  This would tell you up front wether or not to even attempt said critter and you wither move on, or you make your attempt.  Given that you have level limits in EQ2 (effectively the TLC code from EQ), there really is no incentive to come back and take down a critter that is a group or raid level critter alone when you have reached high enough level to solo it, you wont' get any drops, and since the con will be green by then, or grey, you probably won't get any exp.  Let me nail that concept down: the critters con color is level dependent, it's raiting for group or raid (or solo) is independent of level.  Thus, you can find yourself looking at a mob that is a Raid level Grey mob because it's a sufficent number of levels below you.  By the way: I did not see any raid level critters, that I recall, swhile I was doing EQ2, I freely admit that I'm extrapolating from the group level critters i observed.  that said, i'd be very surprised if I'm very far off track with this.  The key point is that you have a secondary method of gauging the difficulty of a mob and thus you have the ability to avoid/tackle mobs that are 'more' appropriate for your situation.  This takes a lot of guesswork out.
<br />

<br />
WoW:
<br />

<br />
Having played Diablo, and WoW, I can say first off, that there is a lot of similarity.  Diablo introduced the concept of the ability tree and WoW adopted this.  This tree allows a decent amount of individualization of character.  However, other than Priest, no character is at a disadvantage so far as soloing is concerned.  Sure, some do it better than others, but, all classes can solo in this game (with the possible exception of the Priest at low levels).  In short, characters in WoW are heroic in their ability.  I was able to either tank, or control the situation to my advantage with all of the classes I played, and I played all classes save the healing classes.
<br />

<br />
Pulling in WoW is a matter of Aggro radius.  If you can catch a critter pathed away from it's friends, you have a solo pull.  If you can't, you will get a multipull.  However, even with multipulls there are mechanisms for taking care of the adds.  Stun, Fear, Sap (similar to mez), or judicious use of a pet, to name a few, are abilities that will allow you to pare off a mob long enough to kill another.  Thus, you can certainly handle a double pull, triples begin to be a problem.  Worst case, run.  Critters in WoW have a short leash, if you run far enough, they will lose aggro, evade any attack, and return home.  That's right, I said they are immune while running back.  Thus, there is no peeling off mobs with an attack as they are returning home, but, rather, you have to go back and try the pull again from scratch.
<br />

<br />
In WoW, there are no group mechanics.  There is only that which makes sense.  ie: you put a tank and a healer together, and (assuming the healer doesn't think he's a tank too) they will do better than putting together two tanks.  However, since any class can stand alone, you will find that groups are just a bunch of soloists come together.  Rarely did I find a Priest who played a Priest.  Rather, I usually found a tank in Priests clothing who never remembered to heal during combat, but was proud that they could rez after everyone had died.  I have to mention that I took a perverse pride in soloing that which I'd been told I could NOT solo in WoW... I also have to tell you that normally i don't like soloing, there is nothing I like more than being in a group that manages to mesh skills and that feeling of invincibility you get when IN a group that meshes well.
<br />

<br />
&lt;note: bear with me, my eyes have been giving me problems of late, so, though I can still type, I can barely read what I'm saying, so, it's making reareading this to gather my thoughts and stay on track difficult.&gt;
<br />

<br />
WoW too has the usual method of conning mobs.  However, unlike EQ, they did a better job of getting the Con on the money.  Ie: if you see an even con, odds are about 50/50 of beating that mob, blue con mobs were fairly easy, greens I can do in droves... fact is, I was able to do reds and oranges (beyond red) with fair ease too... so, maybe I shouldn't say right on but rather overconned.  However, the effect was about right.  If I saw an even con, I knew I could solo it, where as in EQ, if I see an even con, I'm pretty sure I can NOT solo it... in fact, blues in EQ are a test.  That said, there is such a think as an 'Elite" critter in WoW.  This is evidenced by a flare around the target window when targetting the elite critter.  It means that the mob is, essencially, underconned.  However, it's only underconned by a level or two.  I was always able to solo these mobs, I just had to wait one, maybe two, levels beyond the level the mob was intended for.
<br />

<br />
The society in WoW is oddly lacking... and oddly reversed.  I found more folks on the Horde side (evils) willing to give me a hand, and fewer folks begging for handouts, than I did on the Alliance (good) side.  That said, it may well be because i was mostly with the Christmas crowd, and thus with the children on break, but, the overal tenor of the conversations and community was very sniping and caustic.  There were a few calm and stable souls but they were very much crowded out by the rest.  Part of the evidence of this was names.  In WoW I fund a lot more 'caustic' names than I ever saw in EQ (or EQ2).  That said, I'm seeing more and more names in EQ that are... let's just say unsavory.  What irks me about that is that they are often with punctuation (which means a GM had to be involved in the name).  Suffice it to say that I found the siciety in WoW to be lacking, where I did not find it lacking in EQ (or EQ2).
<br />

<br />
In sum:
<br />

<br />
The upside to making classes soloable is that it minimizes down time.  Can't find a group?  Go off and tackle solo content until you can.  The downside is that with no class dependent on others, there is no incentive to group.  further, even when grouped, there is little incentive for the group to really work together to greater advantage.  The greatest example of this that I can think of is what a group does with adds.  In the newer games, an add is handled by someone peeling off and soloing it.  While this is a valid tactic, the fact is that if I can kill as fast solo as I can in group, why group?  If I'm going to be soloing critters in a group, I'm doing nothing that I would not do outside the group.  Further, with no real challenge, there is no need to innovate and come up with new ways to get the classes to work together to greater advantage.
<br />

<br />
This leads to the concept, and importance, of tactics.  If I never have to be innovative about how I take down mobs, it means that I can develop a strategy early in the game and use it through the whole game.  I never really have to change tactics so much as adjust them for new abilities I may gain.  There is no need for researching a method for taking down a specific mob, it will be the same as the last umpteen mobs you took down.  This leads to a stagnant feeling in a game.  Sure, you can play it through again with a second class, or a third, but, after you've tried a few, there it's the same thing over again.  I found this to be especially true of each of the new games.  Even though they are flooded with quests, few of the quests are individualized by race or class.  Thus, if you play a new character, you'll find yourself marching through the same quests... unless you go out of your way to research different ones.  Even this ability is eventualy limited, quicker in some cases (WoW) than others EQ2... CoH falls somewhere in the middle of those two extremes.
<br />

<br />
In the overall, I feel that the games have been dumbed down and much too far.  Pulling is too easy, where it's interesting and I'm forced to adapt to new situations in EQ, I'm not forced into that adaptaion with any of these new games.  While being able to wade through mobs without a care can be fun for a while, ultimately it becomes boring and trite and will not hold the player in the long run.
<br />

<br />
Having a standalone class is fun, while it lasts, but, it doesn't force me to be innovative and thus to grow with the class.  The only growing I do is the obvious growth: leveling.  Without new innovation, and new content really doesn't cut it unless it challenges you to innovate, a game grows stagnent.
<br />

<br />
Society is key.  Being in a society that doesn't reach out and help you can be fun but over time it wears on you and makes the environment caustic and unfun.  Yes, I know that there isn't much that a game design can do to infuence this, but, that effort should be made as a fun environmnent is, ultimately, a more attractive one.
<br />

<br />
I look at most of this and can't help but look back through the years of EQ and the whines that I've read and can't help but think that the dumbing down of hte games was essentially begged for by we the players.  This is especially true, and evidenced iin the new games, by the changing of classes to be standalone as seen in reflection over the years of the 'grass is greener' whines I've read.  Each class, somewhere along the line, has LOUDLY, argued that their class was no good because some other class can do something better.  Which can be translated to: my class doesn't stand alone.  In the short run, standing alone is fun, it makes you feel powerful, in the long run working with ohters to greater affect is better.  It makes for a lot more fun over a much longer time.
<br />

<br />
I'm hiping this came out fairly cogent and will spark debate not on the different games but on the mechanics being adopted by new designs in games.  I personally don't want to play a glorified FPS when I pick up a new MMRPG, I want to play in an environment where I can do well on my own but have great incentive, and reward, from playing with others.  I know that none of these games has really hit the mark: EQ is not very good for soloing, the others have made things too easy in some fashion.  Hopefully, we can come up with some ideas as to how to HIT that mark and make the next generation of games better.
<br />

<br />
Oh, if you read this far, kudos to you... Sorry about being long winded especially since I can't currently read, not well in any case, what I'm typing (odd as that sounds, my eyes are just not focusing well), but, it's a subjec that i've been building up to since experimenting with the other games and since I'm a test engineer (I can't help but compare and contrast what I feel is working, and what's not, because of that training).... and thanks for reading this far.  <img src="images/smiles/icon_smile.gif" alt="icon_smile.gif" border="0" /></span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
</td></tr>
<br />
