<tr><td class="printline">
<span class="name"><a name="97671"></a></span><span class="postdetails">#5:&nbsp;<font color=black><b></b> Author:&nbsp;<b>Ladwen</b>,&nbsp;</font></span><span class="postdetails"><font color=black></font></span>
<a href="viewtopic.php?p=97671#97671"><img src="templates/subSilver/images/icon_minipost.gif" width="12" height="9" alt="Post" title="Post" border="0" /></a><span class="postdetails"><font color=black>Posted: Fri Feb 25, 2005 1:54 am</font><span class="gen"><br>
</td></tr>
<tr><td class="printline">
<span class="postbody">Yeah I seldom read anything in this area, but the title of this post (after edit?) popped up on the index that one could see from the Runes Forum Index, and made me curious enough to read.  It's interesting how calm the author is.  And as a result, I see a lot of arguments about games are really just because many of us have different play styles.  And the most important thing is try to find a game that offers our own play style.
<br />

<br />
For me, I disagree with several things Gnarl stated, but it only comes down to different tastes.  I will try to state them and hope you all see this is not meant to be a final say either.
<br />

<br />
EQ2's visible tags of "solo" and "group" above the mobs jar me out of a fantasy world.  So does its pop-up Heroic Opportunity.  I feel like I'm playing a video game instead of living in a fantasy world where the monsters wander and I as an adventurer need to observe the enemy's movements and figure things out for myself.
<br />

<br />
WoW's big yellow exclamation marks on quest NPCs have the same problem; but for some reason I can forgive it, probably because after a few weeks in EQ2, I grew tired of clicking on every NPC to try to find a quest that I would enjoy.  EQ2 tried to make all the towns real by populating them with a ton of NPCs, but that made getting a quest that suits the player's interest more difficult.  An EQ friend of mine went to try EQ2, and told me he hated it because "the NPCs hassle you."
<br />

<br />
I had played Diablo and did not like it.  Yet I like WoW.  Part of it is I think the combat in WoW is more realistic.  The mobs are congregated around a camp and some of them wander around, which seems very natural from a fantasy's perspective; and as an adventurer I watch them and try to pull the soloing mobs if I'm alone.   With a group we charge into the dense camps.  Only natural.
<br />

<br />
True EQ is a much more tactical game.  Many smart players in EQ have gotten group dynamics down to a science.  The abundant static mobs still seem unnatural to me though.  Plus, if someone in a group and does one thing wrong, everyone jumps on you.  If a tank is poorly equipped, people snicker behind his back and reject him from groups.  In the end I felt EQ became a very elitist world.  For me, that's jut not to my taste.  There was a MMORPG personality test link in the General section of the Runes, and I came out "Socializer, Explorer, Achiever, Killer."  Achievement means a lot less to me than socializing and exploring.  I think that's why camping at one spot bored me.  I love running around doing all sorts of quests in WoW completing each quest area in about 30 min to an hour's time and moving on to another part of the world to explore.   I like discovering a nook here, a stream there with its various mobs around.  I like watching some poor clerics giggle as they say, "I was busy trying to heal the mob."  It all makes the world more fun for me.
<br />

<br />
I like a world where people are not expected to be top-geared and top in tactics.  Socializing, to me, means meeting people of all kinds of personalities and abilities.
<br />

<br />
In EQ I was getting less and less of that because the game punished bad players.  I like casual fun; but many times hunting seemed to be a job more than fun as people all tried hard to perform to the top of their abilities in EQ.  Some players who broke mezz would apologize and say, "I hope you will group with me next time.  Sorry I made a mistake."  And I had to tell them not to worry at all.  And they seemed so relieved, it just didn't feel right to me.  Why should people be expected to be "working" when they are "playing"?
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Rarely did I find a Priest who played a Priest.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
Very true.  Hehehe, my WoW pally was healing every priest I had ever grouped with.  I guess EQ did train us well enough.  Maybe that's why people add my pally to their friend lists a lot.  Thanks to EQ's training grounds.
<br />

<br />
EQ is still the game for the intelligent players.  I admire people who enjoy EQ.  But it's just not right for me.  If you enjoy tactical combat and performing to tough standards, and trying to obtain the top gears, EQ is a great game full of challenges.
<br />

<br />
If you enjoy a casual style of play, WoW is great and down to earth as far as socializing.  I have met many nice people in WoW.  Usually I'm very forgiving on players who make tactical mistakes.  I just feel I'm in an adventurous world where there will bound to be poor fighters, clerics, etc.  (Actually though I'm finding many ex-EQ people in WoW now, and there are some very good players around.)  I feel there is incentive to group since the kill tasks are always faster with a group, and there are many quests (once you pass level 20) that can be done more efficiently by a group.  There doesn't seem to be any trouble finding a group.  I'm in groups every night, and am on many people's friend lists.
<br />

<br />
If you like a fantasy world that is rich with Renaissance atmosphere where you can feel you live in a novel, EQ2 is probably the place.  I think the EQ2 team took a lot of time putting many stories into the world.  But one thing I did not like was the interface.   In many cases the interface was just cumbersome.  Wish it had EQ's interface.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">This leads to the concept, and importance, of tactics.  If I never have to be innovative about how I take down mobs, it means that I can develop a strategy early in the game and use it through the whole game.  I never really have to change tactics so much as adjust them for new abilities I may gain.  There is no need for researching a method for taking down a specific mob, it will be the same as the last umpteen mobs you took down.  This leads to a stagnant feeling in a game.  Sure, you can play it through again with a second class, or a third, but, after you've tried a few, there it's the same thing over again.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
I don't find the lack of tactics stagnant because I'm a socializer.  For me, being able to solo while LFG is like having a nice bar stool to sit in a bar where I can glance around and meet people.  And people of all types of skills and personalities are what keeps a MMORPG game interesting for me.  EQ in the end was getting boring for me because no matter where we hunted, it was the same tactics of "pulling", "CC", "tank", "heal", "debuff", "dps".  That felt stagnant to me.  In fact, I grouped once in EQ2, and immediately saw hunting in EQ2 was built around the same formula.  That was when I decided to quit the game.  I wanted a game where I can socialize without elitism, adventure without having to "work".
<br />

<br />
And be surprised by the outcome when my group rushes a camp.
<br />

<br />
In WoW, I never know what the outcome of a rush for my group toward a camp would be.  Will the cleric next to me freeze and forget to heal? Will the mage over nuke and be killed?  Will we all focus right and get the mobs killed before we are?  It's fun to not know the answer.  It feels real, like I'm just one adventurer in a straggling group, combating madly in a mayhem, trying to keep an eye on all of my teammates to make up for any flaw that may happen any moment due to any number of things.  Because there is no pre-set formula for our tactics.  Everything is on the fly.  That makes it exciting for me.  If we die, I watch how each group member respond.  It's the display of human nature that makes it fun for me.
<br />

<br />
In EQ I can predict most of the fights.  My group always works perfectly 99% of the time.  That makes me fall asleep.
<br />

<br />
I think for others who love a team tactical challenge, EQ is the best game.   EQ2 might be a bit in between WoW and EQ.
<br />

<br />
Even in WoW though, every class needs to think a bit to do well in soloing.  The inept players die a lot while soloing.
<br />

<br />
The trouble I see for all of these MMORPG games is how they will fare in the long run.  EQ is now suffering from all old contents being obsolete.  One day both WoW and EQ2 will reach the same situation where 80% of the older zones are like wastelands.  How should the newer players be brought up to meet the older characters?</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
</td></tr>
<br />
