<tr><td class="printline">
<span class="postbody"></span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">If a tank is poorly equipped, people snicker behind his back and reject him from groups. In the end I felt EQ became a very elitist world.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
Hmm, I've never noticed this kind of attitude.  I've seen people compare gear, and different tanks compare stats to see who should be MA, but I've never seen people get laughed at or kicked out of a group because they didn't have the latest and greatest.  Assuming of course they weren't level 60 and still in bronze...
<br />

<br />
I played UO for a few years and really enjoyed it, for the most part.  I agree about the PvP though, and *hated* that aspect (that you could get killed at any time).  Too many people took advantage of that, and there weren't enough people to self-regulate the PKers.  But I was involved with a player city (Avalon, on the Baja shard), and it was pretty friendly.  We cooperated with other player cities and held events.
<br />

<br />
I remember reading about UO before it came out.  I had all these crazy ideas, before I really knew what was possible.  I read about the craft skills, and that you could be a lumberjack to collect wood, or a miner to collect ore.  I thought I'd be able to actually see trees cut down, and that I could strip a forest bare, then hold all the lumber for ransom.  It's probably a good thing you can't do that, seeing how mean some people can get in-game.
<br />

<br />
I also joked with friends about selling food, but poisoning it.  Then have a partner with a shack just down the road who sold cure potions.  You could poison food in UO, but it didn't really do much.
<br />

<br />
Anyway, yeah, there were good groups in UO that were friendly and some were very creative!  I really like the open-endedness of it.
<br />

<br />
Hmm.  I have a lot more to say, but I'm starting to ramble.  I agree with what you said about UO and EQ. I haven't played any others yet, but don't like the dumbing-down aspect.  I'd like to see an MMORPG that uses more tactics, strategy, and planning.
<br />

<br />

<br />
-- C.</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
