<tr><td class="printline">
<span class="postbody">Juwel:
<br />

<br />
I posted this to rants because I was afraid that I'd get too flamey myself and that the subject might still be SO hot as to cause problems.  This IS a comparison of EQ2 and WoW, as well as EQ and some other games.  I intended it to be more a commentary on the direction that games seem to be taking, and some thoughts as to why they are going that way.  Judging by the current comments, it seems I hit the mark... I was worried I'd missed because, as I said in the post, I literally was having problems reading it back so I just stuck to my guns and didn't edit and rewrite as I wrote (which I normally do).  Feel free to move it to the general boards, or even Dev corner, as it's truly not a rant... I was just worried it would turn into one (given my track record, not an idle concern).  <img src="images/smiles/icon_smile.gif" alt="icon_smile.gif" border="0" />
<br />

<br />
All:
<br />

<br />
I see, and agree to an extent, with the point about being elitiest.  For my part, I've never turned down a person for subpar gear.  I am reticent about asking someone who absolutely refuses to use even minimally reasonable group tactics to join my group.  I'm ok with new tactics and learning, I'm NOT ok with folks doing stupid things when the chips are flying.  Gear, I find, is NOT as important as quality play.  I know that gear can be more telling with some of the mobs, but, I feel that knowing your class, your gear limitations and acting accordingly is key in ALL situations.
<br />

<br />
I too seek fun.  Often, EQ is not much fun anymore because my group(s) also are strack.  We may not be uber geared but we KNOW what we are doing and we can debate many classes points of views and often come up with multiple tactics for a given situation.  The thing is that that ability, that 'professionalism', came about because we had to develop it to survive and get ahead in the game.  If I'm not challenged by a game, I'll be bored more quickly than if I am challenged by it.
<br />

<br />
I'm not discounting socialising and I mean no slight to it.  I've lasted as long in EQ as I have because of the long standing friendships I've made in the game.  The thing that keeps me going in groups is exactly that socialising... but, I'm more awake and aware when in a new situation that I have to face, socialising with the same friends, than I am when I'm facing an old hat situation, with the same friends.
<br />

<br />
An example from EQ is LDoN adventures.  Doing a NRo LDoN for the 300th time is still doing that same map for the same objectives the 75th time (or there abouts).  I can almost do those maps blindfolded and pull them in my sleep.  Don't get me wrong, I like LDoNs, I think it was the single best expansion in the game (this reveals that I'm not into the 'end game' nor am I an uber raider but...)... but... it get's old.  It get's to a point where it's no longer a challenge.
<br />

<br />
Now, take a new game, with characters that can all solo.  That means that the reasons to group are two fold: social and efficiency.  You aren't really doing it for the challenge, save the case where you intentionally go for content out of your league (but you can do that solo), you are doing it to knock out content more quickly.  The point is that with the challenge gone, you are not... well, challenged.  My ideal world has both the challenge AND the society.  So, I can adventure, explore, socialize and feel like I've accomplished something while doing this.  That's missing, for me, in the new games.  The society is there in all cases, but, the challenge is not.  In a nutshell, it's like playing Chutes and Ladders in your teens.  When you were 6 it was a hoot, but in later years you realize there is no challenge to it, no bite, and it loses it's draw.
<br />

<br />
I think that challenge has to be an integral part of a game for it to have longevity.  What I'm saying here is that sure, new games can come out and make a splash and a profit, but, if they are lacking in either Challenge or Society (to name two facets) you will find they have no longevity.</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
</td></tr>
<br />
