<tr><td class="printline">
<span class="postbody">For a warrior to keep aggro, a lot of is in his gear.  And I was always organizing groups so I saw a lot of these rejections.
<br />

<br />
When a game is about tactical challenge for a group, it is only natural for people to want to optimize a group in order to play at the top form of tactics.  This is why EQ tends to encourage elitism.  Toward the end of my EQ days, I was at the top end, and saw folks even rejecting the 2nd top rogue because the top rogue was also in the run for my group.  It just made me feel bad.
<br />

<br />
I agree though tactics does make a game fun.  The thrill of being among top players who all know their stuff is elating; and many of them are nice people.  They are not all snooty.  They just want to try for excellence.  There is nothing wrong with that.  I see their drives and admire them.  But at the same time, EQ was already winding down.  We were having difficulty finding good tanks.  One night my cleric friend moaned at the idea of healing a lesser tank so I watched the lone average-geared warrior LFG for 3 hours while we hunted with an uber beastlord to tank for us instead.  Well, It made me feel bad because, I thought to myself, "He's a nice person, and he's there all by himself LFG.  He may end up leaving EQ."  So I told my group, "We need to take him along, so we can help him develop into a stronger tank."  Well, unfortunately by the time I said this, he had logged.  I never saw him again.
<br />

<br />
EQ designers might have tried to make the game more thrilling in challenges, but it may also have driven away many players that way.  
<br />

<br />
There were other times though, that I had gone out of my way to help young tanks rise, only to see them acting snooty themselves once they did gain good AA and gears.  One turned me down for a group in a flash when he was able to tank in MPG and did not really need a chanter there.  Such is the way of life.  We've all been at both ends of optimal grouping.
<br />

<br />
I think the way to design an MMORPG game to offer tactical challenge lies in developing new styles of challenges that will involve all range of players, including their skill, gear, time available for play.
<br />

<br />
WoW will eventually have challenge on the Battlegrounds, and from what I hear, it will take tactical strategy.  Intelligent players who can lead huge armies with good strategy will become the generals.  Social types like me can go ferry supplies back and forth.  The less geared, less skilled players will some have something to do.  I hope that will work.
<br />

<br />
EQ's big raids is sort of like that too.  Less skilled players can ride along in those raids.  Maybe that's why raids are so popular.  Some classes such as enchanters were pretty boring to play in raids, but I think some classes will be more bored on the Battlegrounds too.  Warlocks, maybe?</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
</td></tr>
<br />
