<tr><td class="printline">
<span class="postbody">P.S.  I loved LDoN too.  Toward the end of it I still had challenges in LDoN because I always tried to help young tanks, wiz, etc. that were level 60 to 62 with very little AAs.  I found out if one member of the group is weak, especially if it's the key role of tanking, it can still bring challenges.
<br />

<br />
It is why I like the idea of some sort of exp or loot bonus for groups that take on this challenge.  EQ's reward system encourages optimal grouping, and discourages people from facing the *challenges* of non-optimal grouping.  Maybe something can be done about this.</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
</td></tr>
<br />
<table width="100%" border="0" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0">
<tr><td class="printline">
<span class="name"><a name="97793"></a></span><span class="postdetails">#13:&nbsp;<font color=black><b></b> Author:&nbsp;<b>Iumuno</b>,&nbsp;</font></span><span class="postdetails"><font color=black></font></span>
<a href="viewtopic.php?p=97793#97793"><img src="templates/subSilver/images/icon_minipost.gif" width="12" height="9" alt="Post" title="Post" border="0" /></a><span class="postdetails"><font color=black>Posted: Sat Feb 26, 2005 12:27 am</font><span class="gen"><br>
</td></tr>
<tr><td class="printline">
<span class="postbody">Great post Gnarl. I'd agree in general except on a few points.
<br />

<br />
There IS an incentive to group in WoW, but pretty much only in instances. The content there is imo every bit as  challenging and fun as old EQ1 if you tackle level-appropriate content. 
<br />

<br />
Regarding the community, I'd say that regarding the pick up crowd, you're right on the money, and skill level in groups is abysmally low, far far below EQ's level. Virtually everyone I've met did not communicate at all after joining the group, and looted every mob they could as soon as it fell if the loot was set at "free for all". Basically it was a bunch of soloers put together in a group and with a single exception every single group I was in worked this way. I think it's interesting that our experience is pretty much the same in that regard.
<br />

<br />
Regarding the game itself, I find that in the more interesting places (instances), WoW is by very far the better game of the three. Better game mechanics, faster paced, more interesting events for single groups. WoW works pretty much the same as EQ except it solved a couple of issues: Little discrepancy between the different classes soloing ability, and no way to single pull beyond picking off roamers. Pulling in EQ lead to all sort of problems, which eventually led to Mob inflation that went out of control and dumbed down the game in it's current tank/healer paradigm. You can still pull in WoW, without the EQ2 incredibly dumbed down system, but groups of mobs usually simply won't split, and this is very, very good, especially with no class really standing out in CC ability, putting the burden of actually having to think and react on every party member. The group content, while admittedly easier as a general rule (but not always), is also much more refined, with mobs along PC power but with special abilities and variety. that you'd usually only find on raid mobs in EQ (AE silence, teleport, charm, etc).
<br />

<br />
This in itself is a very solid base, but it doesn't mean that in the long run that WoW will be the "best" game. Right now it's pretty much only an empty shell, and they are faced with problems associated with the faster leveling. All these nice quests they designed and put hundreds and thousands of hours in are being completed in minutes - in other words, most of the (nice) content they designed is being used up rapidly and they are already faced with the problem of keeping their existing customers.
<br />

<br />
Another problem is that much of their development is devoted to pvping. No offense to the pvpers out there, but this is a dead end. Class balance is even more of an issue in pvp, and pvpers are a loud, high maintenance customer base. As Verant and then sony discovered, you won't get anywhere heading in that direction.
<br />

<br />
So while WoW pretty much stands out as being the best game out there if you go down to the basics, somehow I can't really say it's the best overall game out there. Blizzard is running into problems that quite a few people predicted: Battlenet crowd hurting the community, game too easy, leveling too fast burning up their carefully designed content, lack of content at level 60, and no significant solution to that last problem in sight. They'll have to react pretty fast - something that so far hasn't been part of the blizzard paradigm.</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
</td></tr>
<br />
<table width="100%" border="0" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0">
<tr><td class="printline">
<span class="name"><a name="97801"></a></span><span class="postdetails">#14:&nbsp;<font color=black><b></b> Author:&nbsp;<b>Kadath</b>,&nbsp;</font></span><span class="postdetails"><font color=black></font></span>
<a href="viewtopic.php?p=97801#97801"><img src="templates/subSilver/images/icon_minipost.gif" width="12" height="9" alt="Post" title="Post" border="0" /></a><span class="postdetails"><font color=black>Posted: Sat Feb 26, 2005 2:58 am</font><span class="gen"><br>
</td></tr>
<tr><td class="printline">
<span class="postbody">There is no doubt that EQ is extremely elitist - most of the raid guilds won't group outside guild, or guilds at an equivalent tier; and that's on a very low pop server (Venril Sathir).  Most people in those guilds won't do pickups at all.
<br />

<br />
The reason for this is that, contrary to some posters, gear matters more than skill.  A well geared cleric at 65-70 (and, let's face it, there are no groups below 65) is going to be able to keep a group going in WoS and above; without max ft and tons of extra mana, WoS is their limit, even at 70.  Same goes for other classes.
<br />

<br />
Having no option outside of grouping, which didn't used to be the case pre PoP, means that without fresh blood, you quit.  The raid game is a distraction, one that has kept many people going for years.  EQ has two big problems at the moment, both of which SOE are in denial about - solo group and raid have to be equal in value, with equal rewards; and mobs mustn't scale above players.  WoW has the second one about right, I think.  In EQ, raid gear should never have inflated above tradeskill gear, that is the major cause of discrimination.
<br />

<br />
Without being an alt, a new starter in EQ today doesn't have a clear path through to max level, AAs and gear.  At some point, they have to be carried for a long distance by friends/guild to jump the tracks.  There should always be an opportunity to make a valuable contribution, either to a group, or to your own experience/gear by soloing.  SOE have designed for the max gear/AA player only.
<br />

<br />
About PvP: it really turns me off, but EQ has never given PvP a chance.  Personally, I'm pleased about that.  But it seems to me that making the top end game being mainly PvP would be viable; DAoC seems to have carried it off for years.  In EQ, PvP has never been a viable option, so it is unfair to use EQ as an anti-PvP example.</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
</td></tr>
<br />
<table width="100%" border="0" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0">
<tr><td class="printline">
<span class="name"><a name="97823"></a></span><span class="postdetails">#15:&nbsp;<font color=black><b></b> Author:&nbsp;<b>Nokei</b>,&nbsp;</font></span><span class="postdetails"><font color=black></font></span>
<a href="viewtopic.php?p=97823#97823"><img src="templates/subSilver/images/icon_minipost.gif" width="12" height="9" alt="Post" title="Post" border="0" /></a><span class="postdetails"><font color=black>Posted: Sat Feb 26, 2005 1:35 pm</font><span class="gen"><br>
</td></tr>
<tr><td class="printline">
<span class="postbody">Great read.  I can't comment about EQ2, not having played it (or owning a computer capable since I have a nvidia MX420 video card, from what I've read).
<br />

<br />
I will comment on a few WoW observations.  There are tactics involved, but some are more subtle, possibly merely less developed since the game is quite newer than EQ.  Let me elaborate:  
<br />

<br />
FD pulling was created by EQ players.  Quad kiting, agro kiting, Green pet pulling, and rune tanking were all created by players.  These tactics developed over years, not weeks or months.  Verant (and SoE to a lesser extent) put power in player's hands to develop tactics.
<br />

<br />
In WoW, my main is a rogue.  I read a lot on the wow boards about the uselessness of a top end talent - Vigor (gives the rogue permanent +10 energy).  People posted "how often during a fight do you regen your energy to full?"  My answer - "while soloing higher lever mobs, several times."  In one encounter against several mobs, I encouraged another rogue in my group to attempt "multi sapping", basically sapping grouped targets at the same time.  It works, and works very well.  There are tactics in WoW.  For a good shaman, earthbound totem kiting is excellent - more so in PvP, but it works in PvE nonetheless.  Pet tanking (to handle adds or to replace a missing warrior  / paladin) also works.  Soloing on my druid, cat form shreds casters and bear form helps me take down higher AC and melee damage mobs.
<br />

<br />
The thing about WoW that minimizes the use of creative tactics is that most mobs are roughly equivalent to players in terms of AC and HP, but lacking the multitude of abilities and spells players have at their disposal.  While you can't simply hit autoattack and afk (except perhaps playing a hunter lol), mobs do die fast.  Everything dies fast - especially in a full group.  If something is dead in 10-15 seconds, who cares who's tanking/slowing/mezzing?  This is the downside of creating a game that allows players to solo even con mobs.
<br />

<br />
I've seen the good and bad in WoW groups.  I've wiped to greens in instances because nobody snared (hell - half the players are like "snare?  what's that?") or finished off a runner.  I've seen shaman show up to instance groups that didn't bring any self-rez reagent.
<br />

<br />
I also completed every quest in Western Plaguelands (except the boss in Anderhol) with one group in about 4-5 hours that was avereage level 52.  We had to kill elites +5 of our level, often 2 at a time.  As I reached 50+ in WoW, I noticed that the quality of groups generally improved.  Of course, since it's easy to grind to 60 in the game, level is by no means a guarantee of competency.
<br />

<br />
One somewhat disturbing thing about WoW and tactics is the developers have plainly let it be known that certain player actions are "exploits".  Example would be hunter FD pulling to split out mobs in a certain raid instance or two.  I'm sure there are others that Blizzard has labeled as exploits.  Right now, I'm not sure how I feel about that - but what is apparent is Blizz has placed some limits on player creativity.  Not saying that Verant or SoE haven't done the same thing, but Blizz has done it quickly.
<br />

<br />
One thing about the games you didn't mention were the economies.  To be honest, my initial impressions are that the fundamental game design of WoW in this respect is one that severely limits mudflation.  As the game exists, the best items in the game are Bind on Pickup (both dropped and player quested).  What this means is that the things you need in-game money for are:
<br />

<br />
Repair bills (minimal)
<br />
Consumables / Reagents (higher for some classes than others)
<br />
Level 40 mount (90g and worth every copper)
<br />
Level 60 mount (900g and meant to be a time/moneysink)
<br />

<br />
I recently ran across a post (on blizz boards) consisting of a familiar rant - high end player crafted Armor and Weapons are extremely difficult/expensive to farm/obtain the components to create, and it's generally easier to get dropped/quested items for the time invested.  In my opinion, this is as it should be.  Why?  Well, if player-crafted items (or Bind on Equip - tradeable drops) were the same/better than relatively common instance BoP drops, people could just farm IGE/Yantis for their items (read pay $ for gold) instead of playing the game.
<br />

<br />
WoW is certainly an easier game to play than EQ was for me.  Add in the virtually no-penalty death system, and you get a game that attracts many more people than EQ ever did (and makes most of us more experienced players a lot more forgiving of mistakes).  As you elegantly noted, this is working as intended.  The result is, of course, the community does suffer with the influx of FPS players and general asshats.  What will the community be in the long run?
<br />

<br />
One final note - I created my first Alliance player yesterday (on a different server since I'm PvP) and I pretty much immediately left general chat.  Horde chat on my server, even in Orgrimmar, is not so annoying that I leave it.  On another server, another faction, it was just painful.  Like WoW but hate your community?  Switch factions/servers - gg.</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
</td></tr>
<br />
