<tr><td class="printline">
<span class="name"><a name="97902"></a></span><span class="postdetails">#17:&nbsp;<font color=black><b></b> Author:&nbsp;<b>Gnarl</b>,&nbsp;</font></span><span class="postdetails"><font color=black></font></span>
<a href="viewtopic.php?p=97902#97902"><img src="templates/subSilver/images/icon_minipost.gif" width="12" height="9" alt="Post" title="Post" border="0" /></a><span class="postdetails"><font color=black>Posted: Mon Feb 28, 2005 9:12 am</font><span class="gen"><br>
</td></tr>
<tr><td class="printline">
<span class="postbody">For me: skill > gear.  I've had more problems with folks in uber gear who wipe the group in nothing flat because they can't think beyond their own gear.  Basically, they'd assume that since they had uber gear, everyone else must have, and charge into the fray with no thought of who was backing them up.  Conversely, the folks who don't have uber gear seemed to be forced to work well with their team to get the most out of the group opportunity.  Rather than relying on the gear, they relied on their abilities.  Now, the caveat: we can all pull out examples that sway this either way.  Suffice it to say that Gear and Skill are about equaly important... and imo, should be in future games.
<br />

<br />
In short: you should constantly be pressed to upgrade gear to improve but this need should never be so criitcal that it can create a skill vacuum.  Rather, the two should be complimentary.  Ie: if you get uber_gear_01 which makes you a stat god, you can consistantly stick your foot in it and get clobbered.  Someone with decent gear, and decent skill should, largely, be equivalent to someone with uber gear and no skill OR BAD gear and uber skill.  But, that's an ideal world (and admittedly, my opinion of that world).
<br />

<br />
As for WoW, as a soloist, I found a lot of tactics.  Pulling singles took a LOT of skill.  I could pull singles readily in all save a very few situations I found with all but one of the classes I played (which, again, was all classes save the healers).  Rogues: Sap and kill duels, range pull for others.  Hunter, pull at range, stun if you get a double to split the two, and pet on the incoming.  Mage, range pull for single, freeze any adds.  Warlok, range pulls or stuns, single the left overs.  Etc.  Paladin was the only class I had problems pulling singles with and that class could handle up to three at even or +2 levels, so, I was not very interested in working on single pulls so much (and yes, I know there are techniques for the Paladins to be the premiere pullers, they just didn't fit my role as Paladin AND weren't necessary).
<br />

<br />
I constantly worked mobs 2 and 3 levels my senior in WoW, there was no incentive not to.  The only incentive was the typical incentive: melee versus caster could be dicey.
<br />

<br />
In group, there was no need for tactics, so, all my care and skill as a soloiest... well most of it.. went out the window.  It was just bash away.  I missed needing to work together.  Wether elitist or not, I like being challenged and didn't feel that in WoW.  Ok, there were times when I managed to fubar and overpull, or pull just the wrong mob and I was dead before I knew what hit me, but, that rarely happened and as pointed out the near zero death effects made it meaningless to me.  I'd just go back and rework the scenario.
<br />

<br />
This was made abundantly clear to me when I was clearing the Glaive.  I soloed and Elite with my Hunter, that was at least a level my senior, without even realizing it... I found out it was elite when I looked up to check if the mob was dead yet and realized it had the flames around it's name!  This was just as it died and it went down barely any harder than any other mob.
<br />

<br />
One thing I have to make abundently clear here: I enjoy playing WoW, EQ, EQ2 and CoH, and even aspects of UO.  However, so far, only EQ has the staying power I want.  I want future games to learn from these games and get better.  Unfortunately, i see a lot of improvement in the new games but I don't see them as "better" in the overall.  The key element missing for me is that challenge, that <span style="font-style: italic">need</span> to group that should go hand in hand with the desire to group.
<br />

<br />
Edit: reread it and made a minor tweak for clarity.</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
</td></tr>
